
[1]consume

   CONSUME, v.t. [L., to take. So in English we say, it takes up time,
   that is, it consumes time.]

   1. To destroy, by separating the parts of a thing, by decomposition, as
   by fire, or eating, devouring, and annihilating the form of a
   substance. Fire consumes wood, coal, stubble; animals consume flesh and
   vegetables.

   2. To destroy by dissipating or by use; to expend; to waste; to
   squander; as, to consume an estate.

   Ye ask, and receive not, because ye ask amiss, that ye may consume it
   upon your lusts. James 4.

   3. To spend; to cause to pass away, as time; as, to consume the day in
   idleness.

   Their days did he consume in vanity. Psalm 78.

   4. To cause to disappear; to waste slowly.

   My flesh is consumed away. Job 38.

   5. To destroy; to bring to utter ruin; to exterminate.

   Let me alone-- that I may consume them. Exodus 32.

            CONSUME, v.i. To waste away slowly; to be exhausted.

   Their flesh--their eyes--their tongue shall consume away. Zechariah 14.

   The wicked shall perish--they shall consume. Psalm 37.
